{{multiple issues| {{Orphan|date=April 2011}} {{refimprove|date=May 2013}} }} {{Infobox Organization |name = '''1000 Hills Community Helpers''' |image = |image_border = |size = 225px |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |motto = "Our children are our future." |start date = 1995 |extinction = |type = [[Community organization]] |status = [[Non-profit organization]] |purpose = "To improve the lives of HIV/Aids infected and affected children and adults through treatment, clinics, feeding schemes, counselling, Home-based care, crèches and support groups." |headquarters = [[KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa]] |location = |region_served = South Africa |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = http://www.1000hch.co.za/index.htm |remarks = }}
'''1000 Hills Community Helpers''' is a [[non-profit organization]] in [[South Africa]] devoted to improving the lives of those affected by [[HIV]]/[[AIDS]].
The organization was first established in 1989 by Dawn Leppan and Alan Paton, originally as a program to feed those in poverty and suffering from the effects of HIV/AIDS. After seeing the overwhelming amount of people in need, it was concluded that something more would need to be done, thus founding 1000 Hills Community Helpers.
The Community is located in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], east of the city of [[Pietermaritzburg]] almost to the Indian ocean just north of the coastal city of [[Durban]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction|url=http://www.kznwib.co.za/Portals/125/docs/Appeal%20for%20assistance%20New%20CCC.pdf|work=1000 Hills Community Helpers|accessdate=8 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151953/http://www.kznwib.co.za/Portals/125/docs/Appeal%20for%20assistance%20New%20CCC.pdf#|archive-date=2012-03-22|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> It consists of a health and wellness clinic, children's infirmary, feeding scheme, and education and development facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Mission|url=http://www.1000hch.co.za/index.htm|work=1000 Hills Community Helpers|accessdate=8 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107220549/http://www.1000hch.co.za/index.htm#|archive-date=2010-11-07|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> The clinic is open five days a week, dedicating different days to the elderly, children, open clinic days, and counseling groups for those who need support.
==Founder== Dawn Leppan was raised by her grandparents who owned a restaurant near the main highway which meandered through the Valley, en route to Durban.<ref>{{cite web|title=Start-Up|url=http://www.kznwib.co.za/Portals/125/docs/Appeal%20for%20assistance%20New%20CCC.pdf|work=1000 Hills Community Helpers|accessdate=8 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151953/http://www.kznwib.co.za/Portals/125/docs/Appeal%20for%20assistance%20New%20CCC.pdf#|archive-date=2012-03-22|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> She mirrored her grandmother's humanitarianism and founded the 1000 Hills Community Helpers organization. Leppan has won many awards in recognition for her accomplishments, including the [[Paul Harris Award]].
==Community Clinics== The clinic at the centre operates with the help of retired and volunteer doctors and paediatricians as well as nursing sisters. There is a pharmacy run by a retired pharmacist as well as an emergency ward and a 24-hour emergency service run by Dawn. The aim of the clinic is to improve the lives of babies, children and adults infected and affected by chronic illnesses such as HIV/AIDS, TB, Hepatitis, Diabetes, Cancer, Arthritis and Hypertension.<ref>{{cite web|title=1000 Hills Community Helpers|url=http://www.soulofafricacharity.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=63&Itemid=93|work=Soul of Africa|accessdate=11 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225192014/http://www.soulofafricacharity.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=63&Itemid=93#|archive-date=2012-02-25|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
