'''Eduardo D. P. De Robertis''' (11 December 1913 – 31 May 1988) was a noted [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[physician]] and [[biologist]]. He had a long and prolific scientific career, and was a co-discoverer of cell [[microtubule]]s in 1953.<ref name=NUCRef>{{cite web|title=Eduardo de Robertis biography.|url=http://divulgacion.famaf.unc.edu.ar/?q=ameghino/de-robertis-eduardo|publisher=Faculty of Mathematics and Physics Astronomy, National University of Córdoba|accessdate=27 December 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref>

De Robertis was the son of an [[Italians|Italian]] immigrant<ref>{{cite web|title=Eduardo De Robertis (1913–1988)|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/256133238_Eduardo_De_Robertis_1913-1988|publisher=ResearchGate|accessdate=5 July 2016|language=English}}</ref> and his son [[Edward M. De Robertis]] is also a noted biologist.

In 1981, De Robertis became a founding member of the [[World Cultural Council]].<ref>{{cite web | title = About Us | publisher = [[World Cultural Council]] | url = http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/about-us/ | accessdate = November 8, 2016}}</ref>

