'''Genetic significant dose''' (GSD), or '''genetically significant dose''', was initially defined by [[United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation]] (UNSCEAR) in 1958.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=9525414 | volume=74 | title=An estimation of the genetically significant dose from diagnostic radiology for the South African population, 1990-1991 | year=1998 | journal=Health Phys | pages=419–28 | last1 = Hering | first1 = ER | last2 = Kotze | first2 = TJ | last3 = Maree | first3 = GJ | doi=10.1097/00004032-199804000-00001}}</ref>
It represents an estimate of the [[genetics|genetic]] significance of [[gonad]] radiation doses. Annual GSD is calculated by weighting the individual gonad doses received during [[ionizing]] imaging by the number of individual examined, and accounting for the number of [[offspring]] for each individual.
