'''Smoking in Italy''' has been [[Smoking ban|banned]] in [[public places]] including [[Bar (establishment)|bar]]s, [[restaurant]]s, [[discotheque]]s and [[office]]s since 2005.<ref name="Deutsche Welle 10 01">{{cite news | url= http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,1453590,00.html | title= Smoking Ban Begins in Italy | publisher= [[Deutsche Welle]] | date= October 2005 | accessdate= 6 August 2010}}</ref> A majority of [[Italians]] supported the ban at the time it was first implemented,<ref name="Deutsche Welle 10 01" /> but there was a lack of support from smokers and some bar owners.<ref name="Italians fume" /> 5% of bar and restaurant owners immediately introduced separate smoking rooms.<ref name="Italians fume" />
[[Italy]] was the 4th European country to introduce a smoking ban in public places. On 1 August 2005 a judge ruled that business owners could not be punished for not informing the police about infringing customers. The rates of [[law enforcement in Italy|law enforcement]] are higher in [[Northern Italy]], [[Tuscany]] and [[Sardinia]], with lower rates in [[Southern Italy]], especially in [[Calabria]] (70%) and [[Campania]] (76%).<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.epicentro.iss.it/passi/rapporto2012/FumoPassivo.asp | title= Sorveglianza Passi – Rapporto nazionale Passi 2012: esposizione al fumo passivo | language= Italian | accessdate = 11 August 2013 }}</ref>
[[Heart attack]]s in Italian adults dropped significantly following the implementation of the smoking ban.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/02/080211172539.htm | title= Heart Attacks Decreased After Public Smoking Ban In Italy | publisher= ScienceDaily | date= 12 February 2008 | accessdate = 6 August 2010 }}</ref> The decline in heart attacks was attributed to less [[passive smoking]].<ref name="Michael Kahn">{{cite news | last= Kahn | first= Michael | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL1114668320080211 | title= Heart attacks drop after Italy's smoking ban: study | publisher= [[Reuters]] | date= Feb 11, 2008 | accessdate= 6 August 2010}}</ref> Health Minister [[Girolamo Sirchia]] said that smoking was the leading [[Preventable causes of death|preventable cause of death]] in Italy.<ref name="Italians fume">{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4159587.stm | title= Italians fume over cigarette curb | publisher= [[BBC News]] | date= 10 January 2005 | accessdate= 6 August 2010}}</ref> The ban caused an 8% decrease in [[cigarette]] consumption.<ref name="Roger Dobson">{{cite web | url= http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/331/7526/1159-a/DC1 | title= Italy’s ban on smoking in public places has led to 8% drop in consumption | last= Dobson | first= Roger | publisher= BMJ | date= 19 November 2005 | accessdate = 6 August 2010 }}</ref>
